  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly: "Mentioned in Jer. Chron. for AD 324 as an exceptional orator
    Ausonius also mentions him in the Commemoratio professorum Burdigalensium (14,9)
    he may even have taught at Burdigala/Bordeaux (otherwise [4. 243f.], against [5. 498f.]). 
    His daughter matched him in eloquence (Jer. Chron. AD 336). The surviving panegyric to Emperor 
    Constantinus [1] and the Caesars Crispus and Constantinus [2] II was held at Rome in AD 321 on 
    the occasion of the Quinquennalia of the imperial sons in the absence of the addressees (cf. [3. 338])
    and was adopted into the corpus of the Panegyrici Latini....." iebermann, Wolf-LÃ¼der (Bielefeld). "Nazarius." 
